# Introduction
The Gefieder image is multi-tenant / team data analytics platform built on top of
PostgreSQL, DuckDB, SQLMesh and Django (with Unfold admin interface).

It runs as a small container system managed by podman-compose, consisting of five
containers:

- `postgresql`: the PostgreSQL database holding the engineering and application data
- `crudman`: the Django administration panel, reachable through the proxy
- `sqlmesh`: the SQLMesh analytics engine, executing models on their cron schedules
- `grafana`: the Grafana dashboards, with the PostgreSQL database pre-configured as a
  read-only data source, served through the proxy at https://SERVER_NAME/GRAFANA_PATH/
- `proxy`: an nginx reverse proxy serving the administration panel at
  https://SERVER_NAME/CRUDMAN_PATH/ (plain HTTP in development, see `DEBUG`)


## Configuration

### Settings
The compose project reads its settings from the `.env` file in the repository root.
It is distributed with the repository and contains the following defaults, which you
can adjust to your liking:

```bash
APP_NAME=gefieder
SUPERUSER_NAME=admin
SUPERUSER_EMAIL=admin@nowhere.com
SERVER_NAME=localhost
CRUDMAN_PATH=crudman
GRAFANA_PATH=grafana
```

- `APP_NAME`: the name of the compose project
- `SUPERUSER_NAME`: the name of both the PostgreSQL and the Django superuser
- `SUPERUSER_EMAIL`: the email address of the Django superuser
- `SERVER_NAME`: the public host name of the server, e.g. `myserver.mycompany.com`.
  The administration panel accepts requests for this host name and for localhost.
- `CRUDMAN_PATH`: the base path under which the administration panel is served, e.g.
  `crudman` makes it available at `https://SERVER_NAME/crudman/`.
- `GRAFANA_PATH`: the base path under which Grafana is served, e.g. `grafana` makes
  it available at `https://SERVER_NAME/grafana/`.

### Certificates
In production mode (the default), the proxy needs a TLS certificate for `SERVER_NAME`.
Place it in PEM format in the `proxy/certs/` directory, which is excluded from
version control:

- `proxy/certs/fullchain.pem`: the certificate including intermediates
- `proxy/certs/privkey.pem`: the private key

### Storage
Persistent data lives in two named volumes which podman-compose creates automatically
on the first `podman-compose up`, so no manual step is needed:

- `gefieder_postgresql`: the PostgreSQL data directory (all engineering, analytics and
  application data)
- `gefieder_grafana`: the Grafana dashboards, users and settings

The volumes carry the compose project name (`APP_NAME`) as a prefix. They survive
`podman-compose down`; see the Build and run section for how to inspect or remove
them.

### Secrets
All passwords and keys are stored as managed podman secrets, so they never appear in
the compose file or the images. A secret cannot be overwritten; to replace one, remove
it first with `podman secret rm <name>` and create it again. When creating a secret you
may see a warning like `"/" is not a shared mount`, which is expected and can be
ignored. The trailing dash in the commands below is not a typo, it tells podman to read
the secret from stdin.

Create the Django secret key:
```bash
openssl rand -hex 64 | podman secret create django_secret_key -
```

Create the superuser password. It is used both for the PostgreSQL superuser and the
Django admin superuser. With the command below, you will be prompted to enter the
password interactively without showing it on screen:
```bash
read -s PW && printf "%s" "$PW" | podman secret create superuser_password -
```

Create the password of the `crudman` database user the Django application connects
with:
```bash
openssl rand -hex 32 | podman secret create crudman_password -
```

Create the password of the `sqlmesh` database user the SQLMesh engine connects with:
```bash
openssl rand -hex 32 | podman secret create sqlmesh_password -
```

Create the password of the read-only `grafana` PostgreSQL data source user (the
Grafana admin login uses the `superuser_password` secret instead):
```bash
openssl rand -hex 32 | podman secret create grafana_password -
```


## Build and run
Start the container system from the repository root. The images are built
automatically on the first start. Without further options it runs in production
mode: HTTPS only (see Certificates above), HTTP requests are redirected to HTTPS:

```bash
podman-compose up -d
```

On a development machine, enable debug mode instead. The proxy then serves plain
HTTP without certificates and Django shows debug pages:

```bash
DEBUG=true podman-compose up -d
```

Switching between the modes requires recreating the containers, e.g. with
`podman-compose up -d --force-recreate`.

To force a rebuild after changing a Dockerfile, the application code or the SQLMesh
project, add the `--build` flag:

```bash
podman-compose up -d --build
```

If a rebuild picks up stale layers, rebuild without the cache:

```bash
podman-compose build --no-cache && podman-compose up -d
```

Stop the container system without losing data:

```bash
podman-compose stop
```

Stop and remove the containers:

```bash
podman-compose down
```

The persistent data is kept in named volumes (see Storage above), so neither
`podman-compose stop` nor `podman-compose down` loses it. List the volumes with:

```bash
podman volume ls
```

To remove the containers *and* delete all persistent data, add `-v`:

```bash
podman-compose down -v
```

Note: the proxy publishes the ports 80 and 443, which rootless podman is not allowed
to bind by default. Either allow it once on the host:

```bash
sudo sysctl net.ipv4.ip_unprivileged_port_start=80
```

or publish different ports by setting `HTTP_PORT` and `HTTPS_PORT`, e.g.
`HTTP_PORT=8080 HTTPS_PORT=8443 podman-compose up -d`.


## Test
Before deploying, run the integration test suite. It builds fresh images, starts a
throwaway stack on isolated ports, asserts that the system works (containers start
cleanly, the apps are reachable through the proxy, static files load, the schemas
exist and the read-only `grafana` role has exactly the access it should) and tears
the stack down again afterwards. It is meant to run in isolation, away from any
production system, because the stack it starts is discarded.

The secrets must already exist (see the Secrets section). Run it from the repository
root:

```bash
./run-tests.sh             # dev profile: plain HTTP
./run-tests.sh production  # production profile: HTTPS with a self-signed certificate
```


## Deployment
The following steps deploy the container system on a server:

1. Install `podman` and `podman-compose`. On Ubuntu:

   ```bash
   sudo apt install podman podman-compose
   ```

   On RHEL, `podman-compose` comes from the EPEL repository (or from `pip`):

   ```bash
   sudo dnf install podman
   sudo dnf install epel-release && sudo dnf install podman-compose
   ```

2. Clone this repository and change into it:

   ```bash
   git clone <repository-url> && cd gefieder
   ```

3. Create the five secrets. You will be prompted for the superuser password, the
   others are generated:

   ```bash
   openssl rand -hex 64 | podman secret create django_secret_key -
   read -s PW && printf "%s" "$PW" | podman secret create superuser_password -
   openssl rand -hex 32 | podman secret create crudman_password -
   openssl rand -hex 32 | podman secret create sqlmesh_password -
   openssl rand -hex 32 | podman secret create grafana_password -
   ```

4. Set `SERVER_NAME` in the `.env` file to the public host name of the server, e.g.
   `SERVER_NAME=myserver.mycompany.com`.

5. Place the TLS certificate for that host name in PEM format in `proxy/certs/`:
   the certificate including intermediates as `fullchain.pem` and the private key
   as `privkey.pem`.

6. Allow rootless podman to bind the ports 80 and 443, persistent across reboots:

   ```bash
   echo net.ipv4.ip_unprivileged_port_start=80 | sudo tee /etc/sysctl.d/99-gefieder.conf
   sudo sysctl --system
   ```

7. Open both ports in the firewall. On Ubuntu:

   ```bash
   sudo ufw allow 80/tcp && sudo ufw allow 443/tcp
   ```

   On RHEL:

   ```bash
   sudo firewall-cmd --permanent --add-service=http --add-service=https
   sudo firewall-cmd --reload
   ```

8. Start the system from the repository root. This also creates the named volumes
   for persistent storage (see Storage above):

   ```bash
   podman-compose up -d
   ```

9. Verify the deployment by opening https://SERVER_NAME/crudman/ in a browser and
   checking that a plain http:// request is redirected to https://.

With rootless podman (the default), the containers belong to your user account and
are stopped when your last login session ends. Allow them to keep running without an
open session:

```bash
loginctl enable-linger $USER
```

After a server reboot, the containers do not start automatically; either run
`podman-compose up -d` again or create a systemd user unit that does so at boot.


## Automated deployment
After the first manual deployment above, further deployments can be triggered from
GitHub with the **Deploy to server** workflow (`.github/workflows/deploy.yml`). It is
manually triggered (`workflow_dispatch`) and takes the git ref to deploy as input,
plus a `dry_run` checkbox that runs only the test stage and skips the deployment
(useful for validating the workflow without a server). It runs in two stages:

The **test** job runs the full test suite (`run-tests.sh`) on the GitHub runner, which
has no production stack, so the throwaway test containers never collide with the live
ones. If it fails, the deploy job does not run and production is never touched.

The **deploy** job then SSHes into the server and runs `deploy/deploy.sh`, which:

1. **Backup**: dumps the database with `pg_dumpall` and tags the current container
   images as `:previous`.
2. **Deploy**: rebuilds and restarts the production stack.
3. **Smoke test**: runs read-only checks against the now-running production system
   (`deploy/smoke-test.sh`): containers healthy, the database reachable, HTTP redirects
   to HTTPS, and both apps answer over HTTPS.
4. **Rollback**: if a smoke test fails, restores the `:previous` images and reloads the
   database dump, leaving the previous version running.

The workflow needs these repository secrets (Settings -> Secrets and variables ->
Actions):

- `DEPLOY_HOST`: the server host name or IP
- `DEPLOY_USER`: the SSH user the stack runs as
- `DEPLOY_SSH_KEY`: a private SSH key whose public key is in that user's
  `~/.ssh/authorized_keys` on the server
- `SUPERUSER_PASSWORD`: the superuser password, so the test job can create the same
  podman secret the suite connects with

Generate the key pair locally and install the public half on the server:

```bash
ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -f gefieder_deploy -N ""
ssh-copy-id -i gefieder_deploy.pub DEPLOY_USER@DEPLOY_HOST
```

Then paste the contents of the private key file `gefieder_deploy` into the
`DEPLOY_SSH_KEY` secret. The server is expected to have the repository checked out at
`~/gefieder` (override with the `DEPLOY_DIR` environment variable) with the podman
secrets already created.


## Connect
- Open the Django administration panel at http://localhost/crudman/ in development
  or https://SERVER_NAME/crudman/ in production and log in with `SUPERUSER_NAME`
  and the password stored in the `superuser_password` secret.
- Connect to PostgreSQL with the same password:

```bash
psql -h localhost -p 5432 -U admin -d postgres
```

- Open the Grafana dashboards at http://localhost/grafana/ in development or
  https://SERVER_NAME/grafana/ in production and log in with `SUPERUSER_NAME` and the
  password stored in the `superuser_password` secret. The PostgreSQL database is
  already configured as a read-only data source.
- Follow the SQLMesh engine logs with:

```bash
podman-compose logs -f sqlmesh
```
